<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-234-474  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 234 474.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Data Communications  March 1990 v19 n3 p43(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Affordable fax/data gear on way; Binary File Transfer hasimage-storage potential. (hybrid facsimile/data modems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Jander, Mary; Strauss, Paul R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Medium-speed hybrid facsimile/data modems using onetransmitter/receiver for both functions will soon be available forless than $600 and may serve as a medium for standardizedhigh-quality image transmission.andP;  Current fax boards with modemfunctions separate the two operations, but pending standards willallow the fax portion of the devices to send data.andP;  The low costof fax chips combined with the ability of fax modems to run athalf-duplex 9.6K-bps may let users send data without usingexpensive full-duplex modems.andP;  The Electronic IndustriesAssociation's TR29.1 standards committee is working on problemsentailed in half-duplex data transmissions, including stoppingfaulty transmissions and resending problem blocks, known as BinaryFile Transfer (BFT).andP;  There currently is no standard way to switchbetween data and fax functions; the EIA TR29.2 committee isworking on that problem.andP;  Several hybrid fax/data modems aredescribed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     FacsimileCommunications Boards-CardsNew TechniqueHybrid CircuitsCommunications TechnologyStandardsTransmission SpeedModems.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   The facts about fax/data: hybrid fax/data boards. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>